## Contracts (TypeScript types)
- `HelloMsg { kind:'HELLO', tabId:number, url:string, frameId:number }`
- `SyncMsg { kind:'SYNC', flow?: FlowSnapshot }`
- `StepRequest { kind:'STEP_REQUEST', step: StepSpec, runId:string }`
- `StepResult { kind:'STEP_RESULT', stepId:string, status:'ok'|'retry'|'fail', detail?:any }`
- `IntentMsg { kind:'INTENT', action:'StartFlow'|'Pause'|'Resume'|'Abort'|'ExportLog', payload?:any }`

## Ports vs onMessage
- **Long-lived**: use `chrome.tabs.connect(tabId, {name:'content' })` for content ↔ background; use `chrome.runtime.connect({name:'sidepanel'})` for side panel.
- **One-shots**: `chrome.runtime.sendMessage` for simple triggers from popup.

## Robustness
- On `onDisconnect`, background sets a **reconnect timer** and marks tab as **dehydrated**; content on reload resends `HELLO` to rebind the port.

> Your own README emphasizes “Web Automation Bridge” and typed message contracts—so we codify it here.
